{
  "text": "The diagnosis of IHPS is usually established by abdominal ultrasound, on which IHPS is characterized by increased pyloric muscle thickness length and diameter [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Laboratory evaluation classically shows a hypochloremic, hypokalemic metabolic alkalosis resulting from loss of large amounts of gastric hydrochloric acid, the severity of which depends upon the duration of symptoms prior to initial evaluation [CITATION_3] . Extramucosal pyloromyotomy, introduced by Ramstedt in 1912, still remains the gold standard for surgical management of IHPS [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [23] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . The timing of surgery depends upon the clinical status of the infant. If the diagnosis is made early and the child is well-hydrated with normal electrolytes, then the surgery might take place on the day of diagnosis [CITATION_10] . Surgery should be delayed if there are dehydration and/or electrolyte derangements [CITATION_11] .",
